The paper deals with coding theory and information theory, specifically the properties of Reed-Muller codes and polar codes. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of matrices and subsets, which could fall under cs.CC (Computational Complexity) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The concept of polarization and capacity-achieving codes could also be relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
